          <div style="margin-left: 0px; position: relative; width: 700px; z-index: 5; " id="body_layer">
            <div style="height: 0px; line-height: 0px; " class="bumper"> </div>
            <div id="id2" style="height: 220px; left: 21px; position: absolute; top: 2px; width: 357px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_357_220" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style"><span style="line-height: 28px; " class="style_1">tetr</span> saves <span class="style_2">geom.xyz</span> file automatically (controlled by the option <span class="style_3">XY</span>), so that <a title="http://www.nongnu.org/xmakemol/" href="http://www.nongnu.org/xmakemol/">xmakemol</a> can update it as the geometry changes<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">[<span class="style_4">File ==&gt; Revert</span> every time (sorry!)]. <br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">This is what you see in it now (right): only 2 atoms in the cell.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 283px; width: 300px;  height: 283px; left: 383px; position: absolute; top: 16px; width: 300px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_3 stroke_0 shadow_0">
              <img src="2_files/Screen%20shot%202011-04-17%20at%2011.05.13.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 283px; width: 300px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 252px; width: 266px;  height: 252px; left: 27px; position: absolute; top: 244px; width: 266px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_3 stroke_1 shadow_1">
              <img src="2_files/Screen%20shot%202011-04-17%20at%2011.27.04.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 253px; width: 266px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id3" style="height: 192px; left: 306px; position: absolute; top: 313px; width: 386px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_386_192" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1"><span class="style_5">6.</span> Type <span class="style_3">Bb</span>, and then, when prompted:<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1">              <span class="style_3">-2 2</span> then<span class="style_5"> </span><span class="style_3">-2 2</span> then <span class="style_3">0 0</span><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1">This corresponds to 5 x 5 x 1 supercell - one can clearly recognise the graphene sheet (left).</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id4" style="height: 241px; left: 25px; position: absolute; top: 515px; width: 350px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_350_241" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_5">7.</span> We did not ask for the extension in the 3rd dimension, but if we would, then we need to type <span class="style_3">Bb</span> with e.g.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2">             <span class="style_3">-2 2</span> then <span class="style_3">-2 2</span> the <span class="style_3">0 1</span><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_2">This will show two 5 x 5 graphene sheets stacked on top of each other (right). Type <span class="style_3">B0</span> to remove this “virtual” breeding, <a title="http://www.nongnu.org/xmakemol/" href="http://www.nongnu.org/xmakemol/">xmakemol</a> would only show 2 atoms now (try it!).</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 291px; width: 307px;  height: 291px; left: 367px; position: absolute; top: 463px; width: 307px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_4 stroke_2 shadow_2">
              <img src="2_files/Screen%20shot%202011-04-17%20at%2012.01.50.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 291px; width: 308px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id5" style="height: 319px; left: 348px; position: absolute; top: 771px; width: 350px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_350_319" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_5">8.</span> The cell extensions we did so far were only for visualisation: the actual current cell is still of 2 atoms. To create a supercell, options <span class="style_3">Su</span> or <span class="style_3">Ex</span> can be used. <span class="style_3">Ex</span> will breed the primitive cell “diagonally” by extending existing lattice vectors. Type <span class="style_3">Ex</span> and then<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2">             <span class="style_3">-2 2</span> then <span class="style_3">-2 2</span> the <span class="style_3">0 1</span><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_2">This will form a 5 x 5 cell (left). By using <span class="style_3">Bb</span> again you can make this supercell appear even bigger (try!).</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


